\section{Shell principles}
\label{sec:principles}

%toc:
A shell is a strange beast:
\l \cite{unix-pike}, put quote? (found in abstract of paper about es-shell)
%dup: intro/related-work/sh
it must be both
an interactive command interpreter,
allowing to run commands easily on one line in a terminal, and
a proper programming language,
allowing to write complex scripts in a file.
\l complex program
%
The following subsections unpack this dual nature and
place it in the broader context of terminals, scripting
languages, and the modern revival of the command line.

\subsection{Shell versus terminal}

%claude:
A source of persistent confusion---even among experienced
developers---is the difference between a {\em shell} and
a {\em terminal}. A {\em terminal} (historically a
physical device like a DEC VT100, today a {\em terminal
emulator} like iTerm2, Windows Terminal, or Alacritty)
handles character I/O: it displays characters on a
screen, reads keystrokes, and sends them to whatever
program is attached. A {\em shell} ([[rc]], [[bash]],
[[zsh]]) is the program that reads commands and executes
them. It does not know about screens, cursors, or
fonts---it just reads from file descriptor~0 and writes
to file descriptor~1.

%claude:
The full chain from power-on to prompt makes the roles
clear. At boot, {\em init} (the first process) starts
the system. On a traditional \unix, {\em getty} opens a
terminal device (a serial port or virtual console),
{\em login} authenticates the user, and {\em login}
starts the user's {\em shell}. On \plan, [[init]] starts
[[rc]] directly, and [[rio]] provides virtual terminals
(each window IS a terminal that gets its own [[rc]]).
On a modern laptop, the terminal emulator plays the role
of getty: it creates a pseudo-terminal device, forks a
shell, and connects the two. The shell never knows
whether it is talking to a physical VT100, an
[[xterm]], or a [[rio]] window---all it sees is a file
descriptor.

